name: benzo[b]thiophene-3-acetic acid
Reason: The compound benzo[b]thiophene-3-acetic acid can be broken down into the following functional groups and structural elements: the benzo[b]thiophene base structure, the carboxylic acid (acetic acid) group, and the interaction between them. The basic unit here can be considered as thiophene, which has a melting point of around -38°C. The benzene ring fused to thiophene will increase the planarity and rigidity, increasing the melting point. Each benzene ring generally adds about 40°C to the melting point. The thiol (SH) in thiophene is replaced by a sulfur (S) atom in benzo[b]thiophene, which would likely contribute a slight increase due to increased molecular weight and van der Waals interactions, estimated around 10°C. The acetic acid group typically adds about 50°C to the melting point due to its ability to form strong intermolecular hydrogen bonds. With these considerations, the predicted melting point for benzo[b]thiophene-3-acetic acid can be estimated by adding these contributions together.
Prediction: For thiophene as the base, starting at -38°C: adding 40°C for the benzene ring, 10°C for the sulfur atom instead of SH, and 50°C for the acetic acid group, we get an estimated melting point of (-38 + 40 + 10 + 50)°C = 62°C.
